'''Kollam Municipal Corporation''' (KMC) is an [[ISO 9000#Contents of ISO 9001:2015|ISO 9001:2015]] certified civic body that governs the [[Kollam|City of Kollam]] in the Indian state of Kerala.<ref>{{cite|url=http://lsgkerala.gov.in/index.php/en/news-district-news/kollam-corporation-achieved-iso-certification-1636 |title=Kollam Corporation achieved ISO Certification |date=17 May 2019 |accessdate=18 June 2019}}</ref><ref>[http://kerala.gov.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=3735&Itemid=2583 Municipal Corporations in Kerala - Kollam]</ref><ref>[http://www.indiamapped.com/municipal-corporation-in-india/kollam-municipal-corporation/ Kollam Municipal Corporation Details]</ref><ref>[http://www.getit.in/kollam/corporation-zonal-office/kollam/3379054.html Corporation zonal office, Kollam]</ref> It is the fourth largest city corporation in the state by population and fifth largest by area. Constituted in 1903 and officially recognized as city corporation in 2000,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.townplanning.kerala.gov.in/Urban%20Policy.html |title=Office of the Chief Town Planner |publisher=Townplanning.kerala.gov.in |date= |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> the body governs an area of {{convert|73.03|km2}} centered on Kollam  with about 55 wards and a population of 397,419.<ref name=Cities1Lakhandabove>{{cite web | url=http://www.censusindia.gov.in/2011-prov-results/paper2/data_files/India2/Table_2_PR_Cities_1Lakh_and_Above.pdf | format=PDF | title=Provisional Population Totals, Census of India 2011; Cities having population 1 lakh and above | publisher=Office of the Registrar General & Census Commissioner, India}}</ref>

Kollam is the 2nd most revenue generating city in Kerala. As of 2015-16 reports, Kollam has a revenue of Rs.889.74 crore, expenditure of Rs.830 crore and a surplus of Rs.59.73 crore.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/revenue-augmentation-gets-thrust-in-kollam-civic-budget/article8278527.ece |title=Revenue augmentation gets thrust in Kollam civic budget |publisher=The Hindu |date= |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kollamcorporation.gov.in/financial-statements |title=Financial Statements - Kollam Municipal Corporation |publisher=KMC Official Website |date= |accessdate=2016-08-15}}</ref>

==History==

[[Kollam]], known historically as Quilon, was an ancient trade hub and one of the largest port cities in Asia.<ref>{{cite news|author=Ignatius Pereira |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/emergence-of-antiques-triggers-treasure-hunt-in-kollam/article5711850.ece |title=Emergence of antiques triggers treasure hunt in Kollam |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=2014-02-21 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Ignatius Pereira |url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/shards-of-the-past-point-to-kollam-ports-glory-days/article5728896.ece |title=Shards of the past point to Kollam port’s glory days |publisher=[[The Hindu]] |date=2014-02-26 |accessdate=2014-06-06}}</ref> The population density of the coastal belt of [[Kollam]] is very high compared to any other city in the state. After the constitution of [[Kochi]] as a corporation in 1967, there were intense demands to upgrade the densely populated Kollam City into a city corporation. As a result, on 1{{nbsp}}October 2000, Kollam Municipality was upgraded by the Kerala Government to a Municipal Corporation.

The city population of Kollam increased substantially from 139,852 in 1991 to 346,013 in  2011. In 1991,  the [[Vadakkevila]], [[Sakthikulangara]], [[Eravipuram]] and [[Kilikollur]] [[panchayat]]s were merged with Kollam City. As a result, the area run by the municipal corporation increased from {{convert|18.48|km2}} to {{convert|58.18|km2}}.<ref name="jnnurm.nic.in">[http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/16-Kollam-Draft-Report.pdf Rapid Baseline Assessment in Kollam City - Ministry of Urban Development] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140714182244/http://jnnurm.nic.in/wp-content/uploads/2014/03/16-Kollam-Draft-Report.pdf |date=2014-07-14 }}</ref> Later in May 2015,  [[Thrikkadavoor]] panchayath is merged with [[Kollam]] city and total population of the city became 397,419 with total area of {{convert|73.03|km2}}.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/thrikadavur-becomes-part-of-kollam-city/article7300668.ece |title=Thrikadavur becomes part of Kollam city |publisher=The Hindu |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://lsgkerala.in/thrikkadavoorpanchayat/general-information/ |title=Thrikadavur Panchayath |publisher=Thrikadavur Panchayath |accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref>

==Structure==

